<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Natural disturbance is primarily flood-driven. Trees are top-killed by even, low-intensity fires and are susceptible to fungal pathogens. Trees sprout from stumps, charred boles, root crowns, or lateral roots following fire. Older trees sprout less than younger ones. Historic fire regimes are understudied, but it is expected that fires are less frequent than on adjacent uplands. When fires do occur, they are most severe in older cottonwood stands where fuel accumulation is high (Steinberg 2001a). Many stands in southern California and the Central Valley have been invaded by <i>Arundo donax, </i>frequently increasing fuel load and fire intensity and reducing fire intervals, which can lead to high mortality of native cottonwoods and willows and increased post-fire dominance by <i>Arundo </i>(Coffman 2007, B. Orr pers. Comm. 2007). Montane stands were likely once more continuous in the landscape; however, the narrow riparian stands have been shaded out and fragmented by fire exclusion and conifer encroachment (N. Sugihara pers. Comm. 2007).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium to long
				
