    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af-h, Aj-l). Stands occur along the lower Carmel River and along streams in the Big Sur coast.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ae-f, Ah). Small stands occur along Arroyo Seco in Monterey Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-m, Ap-u). Individual trees and small stands occur along the Klamath and Trinity rivers at low and montane elevations throughout the section. Large stands exist at the north end of Trinity Lake and in the upper ranges of the Sacramento and Scott rivers.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gf, Gj, Gp). Stands occur along streams and stream terraces in this section (S. Smith 1998b), such as those emerging from the Warner Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341De, Dh, Dj, Dl). Stands occur along several of the eastside drainages of the Sierra in the Mono Basin. Most of these are small and intermixed with stands of several willow alliances. Stands with conifers, such as <i>Pinus jeffreyi</i> and <i>Abies concolor,</i> exist along Buckeye Creek near Twin Lakes and other drainages flowing into Bridgeport Valley (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ad-g). Large stands occur along the lower reaches of the Eel, Klamath, and Mad rivers. These occupy low terraces adjacent to the active channels and are primarily within 25 km of the coast.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-b). Individual trees and stands occur along the larger reaches of streams; the most noticeable are along the Eel and Russian rivers.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-k, Em-o, Eq-r, Eu). Stands occur mostly at montane elevations (Potter 2005), including relatively large stands along streams flowing through glacial valleys of Yosemite and Kings Canyon national parks. Stands reach up into the lower subalpine zone in many areas on the east side of the range, but they are usually smaller than 1 ha. On occasion, stands may take on a shrubby appearance, and shrubs can be abundant as conifer forest understories (Potter 2005). Small stands occur along many of the southeastern Sierra streams. Stromberg and Patten (1992) reported tree densities along streams in Inyo Co. Trees with narrow leaves in this section are <i>P. angustifolia</i> (UCB 2004, 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb). Griffin and Critchfield (1972) depicted isolated occurrences in the Inyo Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-e, Bi). Stands are occasional in the Los Angeles Basin, along the Ventura and Santa Clara rivers, and along the Ojai and Sespe creeks (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007). A few small stands occur along semipermanent streams on Santa Cruz Island.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba, Bc-g, Bj-p). Zembal (1989) reports tree density and cover along the Santa Margarita and Santa Ana rivers. However, stands are not common in this section; <i>P. trichocarpa</i> trees occur in other riparian types such as of the <i>Platanus racemosa</i> alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da-j, Dl-m). Stands exist mostly at montane elevations (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Populus trichocarpa </i>rapidly recovers from disturbed areas either by sprouting or by colonizing with rapid stabilization of sites, and stands are relatively resistant to erosion and disturbance (Potter 2005). Regular flooding disturbance in high-energy mountain streams tends to minimize stand size, and bed and bank alteration along lower reaches of coastal streams has reduced stands. Changes in flooding regimes as the result of dams on some rivers and streams have reduced the extent of the alliance (Braatne et al. 1996). Most original stands along the coast are now agricultural fields and pasture. </div>
</div>

    

    

